    Demo Case 07 - Open / Complaint / High priority
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the SEVENTH of the 10-case demo dataset; together with
    cases 01 through 06 and cases 08 through 10, it satisfies the AAP
    requirement (Section 0.7.4) of "at least 10 demo cases across all
    six statuses and both case types," and contributes to the dataset
    matrix:

        Case 01 - Draft       / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 02 - Open        / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 03 - In Progress / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 04 - Pending     / General Inquiry / Low
        Case 05 - Resolved    / General Inquiry / High
        Case 06 - Closed      / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 07 - Open        / Complaint       / High      ## THIS FILE
        Case 08 - In Progress / Complaint       / Critical
        Case 09 - Resolved    / Complaint       / High
        Case 10 - Closed      / Complaint       / Critical

    The 10-case dataset thus exercises:
      * Every one of the six statuses (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed) - this case populates the Open slot for the
        Complaint type
      * Both case types (General Inquiry and Complaint) across the
        full lifecycle - case 07 is the canonical OPEN COMPLAINT, the
        Complaint-flow analog of case 02 (Open General Inquiry), AND
        is THE FIRST COMPLAINT CASE in the fixture (cases 01-06 are all
        General Inquiry; cases 07-10 are all Complaint)
      * All four priorities (Low, Medium, High, Critical) - this case
        contributes one of three High-priority entries to the
        all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar chart (alongside cases 05
        and 09)

    Lifecycle position - WHY Open / Complaint / High is meaningful:
      A Complaint case at the Open status has traversed Draft -> Open
      via the validate_open_transition subflow (which requires
      assigned_group to be populated). The case has been routed to the
      demo team's queue but has NOT yet been picked up by an agent;
      assigned_agent therefore remains empty. The case will progress to
      In Progress only when a case_manager assigns an agent who is a
      member of the assigned_group, satisfying the
      validate_inprogress_transition subflow's two-clause guard
      (assigned_agent populated AND member of assigned_group).

      High priority is appropriate for an unassigned complaint at intake:
      complaints typically warrant elevated urgency relative to General
      Inquiries (case 02 Open General Inquiry is Medium), and the High
      priority signals to the manager that this complaint should be
      triaged ahead of routine General Inquiries. The priority is set
      at intake by either the portal submission widget or the manager's
      initial form save and is independent of the lifecycle status.

      This case is THE FIRST COMPLAINT CASE in the fixture: it marks
      the boundary between General Inquiry cases (01-06) and Complaint
      cases (07-10). Without this case (and its three Complaint
      siblings), the all_cases_by_type Manager View donut would have an
      empty Complaint slice, defeating the dashboard's two-type
      demonstration.

    Role / cross-dependency context (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This case DEPENDS ON (loaded BEFORE this record):
        - The scoped application records under ../../app/
            (sys_app and sys_scope; this case's <sys_scope>/<sys_package>
             reference fields resolve via the source attribute against
             those records)
        - The case table definition at ../../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml
            (this record's <sys_class_name>x_[scope]_case</sys_class_name>
             requires the table to exist)
        - All dictionary entries for the case table under
            ../../dictionary/x_[scope]_case_*.xml  (every populated
            field below requires its dictionary entry to be present)
        - All choice records under ../../choices/  (the type=Complaint,
            status=Open, and priority=High choice values must be
            registered)
        - The auto-numbering record at
            ../../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case.xml  (defines the
            CASE0000001 format; this record's <number/> is intentionally
            empty so the platform auto-generates per that format on
            insert)
        - The role records under ../../roles/  (the demo agent's read
            access requires the x_[scope]_case_agent role and its ACLs
            with the "Assigned only" group-membership clause)
        - The ACL records under ../../acl/  (table-level and field-level
            ACLs gate read/write access; this case is visible to the
            demo agent ONLY via the group-membership clause of "Assigned
            only" since assigned_agent is empty)
        - The business rule records under ../../business_rules/
            (set_opened_date Before-Insert auto-sets <opened_date> on
             this case at import time; block_draft_backtransition will
             prevent any future Open->Draft attempt;
             validate_assigned_agent_membership will fire IF and WHEN
             an assigned_agent is later set)
        - The state-machine flows under ../../flows/  (specifically
            ../../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml, which governs
            this case's lifecycle with the OnUpdate trigger filtered by
            type=Complaint; the Open -> In Progress transition is gated
            by the validate_inprogress_transition subflow at
            ../../flows/sub_flows/validate_inprogress_transition.xml)
        - ../groups/sys_user_group_x_[scope]_demo_team.xml  (referenced
            by <assigned_group>; resolved by name lookup; THIS CASE DOES
            NOT REFERENCE A USER for the assigned_agent slot - the
            agent has not yet picked up the case)

      This case IS REFERENCED BY (loaded AFTER this record):
        - NONE under ../tasks/  (Open cases have no demo tasks; the
            seed-script's task table includes tasks ONLY on cases 03,
            04, 05, 08, 09; this case (07) has zero child tasks because
            the agent has not yet started work)
        - NONE under ../parties/  (Open cases have no demo parties; the
            seed-script's party table includes parties ONLY on cases 03,
            04, 05, 08, 09; parties are typically captured during the
            investigation phase, not at intake)
        - The case_count_by_status Agent Workspace donut at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_case_count_by_status.xml  (this
            case populates the Open slice along with case 02)
        - The all_cases_by_status Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_status.xml  (this case
            populates the Open bar along with case 02)
        - The all_cases_by_type Manager View donut at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_type.xml  (THIS CASE
            POPULATES THE FIRST ENTRY OF THE COMPLAINT SLICE; without
            cases 07-10, the Complaint slice would be empty)
        - The all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_all_cases_by_priority.xml  (this
            case populates one of three High entries; cases 05 and 09
            are the others)
        - The cases_opened_30d Manager View single-score widget at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_cases_opened_30d.xml  (since
            opened_date is auto-set to "now" by the set_opened_date
            business rule at insert time, this case is included in the
            count of cases opened within the last 30 days)
        - The avg_time_to_close Manager View single-score widget at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_avg_time_to_close.xml  (this case
            does NOT contribute because the widget filters on
            status=Closed; only cases 06 and 10 contribute to the
            average)
        - The my_open_cases Agent Workspace list at
            ../../reports/x_[scope]_my_open_cases.xml does NOT include
            this case for the demo agent: the list filter is
            "assigned_agent = current user AND status NOT IN (Resolved,
            Closed)", and assigned_agent is EMPTY on this case. The
            demo agent CAN see this case via the case list backed by
            the read-agent-assigned ACL (group-membership clause), but
            it does not appear on the personal "My Open Cases" widget.
        - The "Assigned only" ACL test (Validation Gate 3 ACLs):
            THIS CASE IS THE CANONICAL GROUP-MEMBERSHIP-CLAUSE TEST.
            The case_agent ACL condition is:
              current.assigned_agent == gs.getUserID() ||
              gs.getUser().isMemberOf(current.assigned_group.toString())
            On this case, the FIRST clause is FALSE (assigned_agent is
            empty). The SECOND clause is TRUE because the demo agent
            is a member of x_[scope]_demo_team. Therefore the demo
            agent CAN read this case via the group-membership clause.
            This contrasts with cases 03, 04, 05, 08, 09 where BOTH
            clauses grant access (since both fields are populated).
        - The Open -> In Progress transition guard test (Validation
            Gate 2): when an operator (acting as case_manager) attempts
            to transition this case to In Progress without first setting
            an assigned_agent, the validate_inprogress_transition
            subflow blocks with a form-level error. This is the
            COMPLAINT-flow analog of the same test on case 02 in the
            general_inquiry flow; both flows MUST surface identical
            blocking-error behavior per AAP Section 0.5.5.

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's ten authoring rules):

      Rule 1 - Synthetic only (AAP Section 0.7.2 NO-PII clause):
        subject       = "Demo case 07: Open (Complaint)"
        description   = "Synthetic Open complaint case awaiting agent
                         assignment." (no PII; the wording emphasizes
                         the lifecycle position - the case has been
                         opened by intake but is awaiting agent pickup)
        requester_name  = "Synthetic Requester Seven" (synthetic
                          identifier using the literal word "Synthetic"
                          plus the numeral spelled out for the requester,
                          NOT a real person's name; matches the
                          spelled-out convention used by all 10 demo
                          cases for the requester_name field)
        requester_email = "requester-7@example.invalid"
                          (RFC 2606 / BCP 32 reserved .invalid TLD never
                          resolves to a real domain; the local part uses
                          the NUMERAL "7" matching the file numbering,
                          NOT the spelled-out word "seven" - this is a
                          deliberate design choice consistent with the
                          file's idempotent file-name convention and
                          matches the pattern used by every other case
                          (requester-1 through requester-10))

      Rule 2 - No auto-number override:
        The <number/> element is intentionally absent. The auto-number
        engine defined in ../../numbers/sys_number_x_[scope]_case.xml
        generates a CASE0000001-format value on insert per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (the "number" row of the case schema specifies "Auto-
        number" with format CASE0000001 and Read-only constraint).

      Rule 3 - Auto-set opened_date (NO explicit override):
        The <opened_date/> element is intentionally absent. The
        set_opened_date Before-Insert business rule at
        ../../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_opened_date.xml fires on
        record insert and sets opened_date = gs.nowDateTime(). On a
        fresh PDI import this yields an opened_date "now," which:
          (a) places this case correctly in the cases_opened_30d
              single-score widget (since "now" is trivially within 30
              days)
          (b) keeps the demo dataset chronologically realistic relative
              to import time
          (c) avoids any need for explicit date overrides (unlike
              cases 06 and 10, which require explicit dates to make
              the avg_time_to_close widget meaningful for Closed cases;
              Open cases have no closed_date and thus contribute
              nothing to that widget anyway)

      Rule 4 - No closed_date in Open:
        The <closed_date/> element is intentionally absent. The
        closed_date field is auto-set ONLY by the set_closed_date
        Before-Update business rule at
        ../../business_rules/x_[scope]_set_closed_date.xml on the
        Resolved -> Closed transition. Since this case is at Open (not
        Closed), closed_date MUST remain null. Setting closed_date on a
        non-Closed case would corrupt the avg_time_to_close Manager
        View widget, which filters on Closed status and averages
        (closed_date - opened_date).

      Rule 5 - Mandatory assigned_group, NO assigned_agent, NO
               pending_reason:
        assigned_group = "x_[scope]_demo_team"  (mandatory because the
                         case had to traverse Draft -> Open via the
                         validate_open_transition subflow's
                         "assigned_group populated" guard per AAP
                         Section 0.5.5; the demo team is the team
                         responsible for triaging this complaint)
        assigned_agent = (absent / unpopulated)  (Open cases have NOT
                         yet been picked up by an agent; assigned_agent
                         is set only when the case_manager assigns the
                         case to an agent during the Open -> In
                         Progress transition, which is gated by the
                         validate_inprogress_transition subflow's
                         two-clause guard "assigned_agent populated AND
                         member of assigned_group" per AAP Section
                         0.5.5; this case represents the pre-In-Progress
                         lifecycle state)
        pending_reason = (absent / unpopulated)  (Open cases never
                         carry a pending_reason; pending_reason is set
                         ONLY when the case transitions In Progress ->
                         Pending, and is cleared by the
                         clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress business
                         rule when the case transitions Pending -> In
                         Progress; this case has never been at In
                         Progress and has never been at Pending)

      Rule 6 - Choice value precision:
        type     = "Complaint"   (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml; the second
                   of the two case types; capital C deliberate -
                   "Complaint" not "complaint" or "COMPLAINT" or
                   "Complaints"; note this is the FIRST Complaint case
                   in the fixture, marking the General-Inquiry-to-
                   Complaint boundary at the case_07 -> case_08 hinge)
        status   = "Open"        (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml; the
                   second of the six statuses, between Draft and In
                   Progress; capital O deliberate - "Open" not "open"
                   or "OPEN")
        priority = "High"        (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml; the
                   third of the four priorities, between Medium and
                   Critical; capital H deliberate - "High" not "high"
                   or "HIGH")

      Rule 7 - Zero hardcoded sys_id cross-references (AAP Section
               0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals anywhere"):
        The case's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key,
        which is acceptable per the AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to
        any other record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase
        hex value computed at file generation time as the MD5 of the
        idempotent subject "Demo case 07: Open (Complaint)" =
        d2a92d7d0645409519a05256350fc65e - so the Update Set engine
        resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import, making the record
        idempotent.

        EVERY cross-reference field below uses the stable human-readable
        lookup key (name / scope source) as both the display_value
        attribute AND the text content - NOT a hardcoded sys_id literal.
        This matches the convention established by every peer file in
        the scoped Update Set (sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, dictionary/x_[scope]_*, etc.) and complies
        with the AAP Section 0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals anywhere" rule:
          - <assigned_group display_value="x_[scope]_demo_team">
                x_[scope]_demo_team
            </assigned_group>  resolves by name lookup against
            sys_user_group; the platform's reference-resolution engine
            looks up the group's sys_id from its name at import time.
          - <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_[scope]</sys_scope>
                resolves by scope source-name lookup against the
                sys_scope record at ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml
          - <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_[scope]">
                x_[scope]
            </sys_package>  resolves by scope source-name lookup; the
            additional source attribute is required by the Update Set
            engine for scope-package binding
        NOTE: there is NO <assigned_agent> element below because Open
        cases have not yet been picked up by an agent. The absence of
        the element is itself the encoding of that lifecycle fact.

      Rule 8 - Scope binding:
        <sys_scope>   binds this case row to the scoped application via
                      the scope source name "x_[scope]" defined in
                      ../../app/sys_scope/x_[scope].xml at
                      <source>x_[scope]</source>; the display_value
                      "Case Management" matches the sys_app's human-
                      readable name (the sys_app's <name> is "x_[scope]
                      Case Management", and "Case Management" is the
                      conventional display label).
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the additional
                      source="x_[scope]" attribute that is required by
                      the Update Set engine for scope-package binding.
        Both fields together ensure this case is tracked as part of the
        scoped application's Update Set and not in any other scope.

      Rule 9 - Idempotency anchor:
        The case's idempotent key is <subject> =
        "Demo case 07: Open (Complaint)". The companion seed script
        ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js is expected to query
        x_[scope]_case by subject BEFORE inserting; the
        action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner
        <x_[scope]_case> element ensures the same behavior at Update
        Set import time. The subject value MUST EXACTLY match the
        seed script's case-table entry for this case.

      Rule 10 - Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element: <record_update table="x_[scope]_case">
        Inner element: <x_[scope]_case action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
        idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1 round-trip-
        verification.
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Element ordering within inner element: alphabetical (matching
        the convention used by every other XML in the scoped Update
        Set).
        Unix-style line endings (LF only, no CRLF).
        No BOM.
        The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved verbatim in the
        sys_class_name, sys_update_name, all reference values, and the
        file path; the PDI auto-assigns the actual concrete scope id at
        App Engine Studio creation time, and the Update-Set apply-time
        substitution propagates consistently across all bracketed
        placeholders.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/
        java/com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        ArkCase's central JPA entity for the case domain. Implements
        AcmObject, AcmEntity, AcmAssignedObject, AcmNotifiableEntity,
        AcmStatefulEntity, AcmLegacySystemEntity, AcmParentObjectInfo,
        AcmContainerObject, AcmChildObjectsManager. The ArkCase entity
        carries ~80+ fields including identity, numbering, classification,
        title, status, descriptive details, incident timestamps, audit,
        disposition, priority, queue/response timing, courtroom/
        responsibility, ECM container linkage, and child associations.
        ArkCase's case discriminator (cm_class_name for single-table
        inheritance) is REPLACED in the target by a simple type Choice
        field with values "General Inquiry" and "Complaint" per AAP
        Section 0.5.7. The 12-field schema in the AAP captures only the
        subset required by the POC; ECM container linkage, milestones,
        participants, and many other fields are explicitly out of scope.
        Default status = "DRAFT" in ArkCase; the queue handler
        (CaseFileQueueHandler) sets status to "ACTIVE" on save. In the
        target, the status choice list uses "Draft" / "Open" / etc. with
        normal capitalization; this case's status="Open" is the
        ServiceNow-convention analog of ArkCase's "ACTIVE" post-queue
        status.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag,
        after substituting the [scope] placeholder for testing) returns
